# gpsim command script: drive the PIC10F322 footswitch and snapshot PORTA/LATA.
#
# WHAT THIS IS
#   A register-level functional check of the PIC shell (bypass_mcu_pic10f322.c)
#   running inside gpsim. The pure debounce core and the output drivers are
#   already covered by the host/formal suite and (on AVR) by simavr lock-step;
#   the PIC SHELL -- oscillator/TMR2 tick, footswitch read on RA3, the debounce
#   integrate/step wiring, and the GPIO outputs -- has no simavr equivalent, so
#   this drives the real built HEX in gpsim and asserts the observable register
#   state at four settled checkpoints. The wrapper test/pic/run_gpsim_test.sh
#   parses the snapshots and turns them into PASS/FAIL.
#
# HOW IT IS RUN (see the wrapper / `make pic-test-gpsim`)
#   gpsim -i -pp10f322 <variant>.hex -c test/pic/footswitch_toggle.stc
#   The HEX (any of the three variants) is supplied on the gpsim command line, so
#   this script is variant-agnostic. gpsim names the PIC pins ra0..ra3.
#
# PINS (per src/bypass_pins_pic10f322.h)
#   RA3 = footswitch (input; high = released, low = pressed)
#   RA0 = status LED  (LATA bit 0; high = effect ENGAGED, low = BYPASS)
#   RA1/RA2 = the active variant's control output(s)
#
# TIMING
#   FOSC = 2 MHz -> instruction clock FOSC/4 = 500 kHz -> 500 cycles per 1 ms.
#   The debounce needs PRESSED_THRESH(8) low samples to register a press and
#   RELEASE_THRESH(25) high samples to re-arm; the relay/mute drivers also block
#   ~12 ms per actuation. All checkpoints below are placed well clear of those
#   windows so every variant has SETTLED by the time it is sampled.
#
# SCENARIO (two MOMENTARY presses; the effect latches between them)
#   cyc      0..12.5k : released  -> BYPASS (power-on default)
#   cyc 12.5k..27.5k  : press #1  (~30 ms)  -> toggles to ENGAGED, then released
#   cyc 27.5k..65k    : released, effect stays ENGAGED (latching)
#   cyc 65k..80k      : press #2  (~30 ms)  -> toggles back to BYPASS
#
# CHECKPOINTS (the wrapper keys on these exact === labels ===)
#   INIT_BYPASS  @ 11.25k : LATA bit0 == 0 (LED off), PORTA bit3 == 1 (released)
#   PRESS1_EARLY @ 15.5k  : LATA bit0 == 0 (LED still OFF), PORTA bit3 == 0 (pressed).
#                         This is 3.0k cyc (~6 ms) AFTER the press edge (12.5k) but
#                         ~1.0k cyc (~2 ms) BEFORE the earliest legitimate toggle (~16.5k =
#                         12.5k + PRESSED_THRESH*500). It pins that the TICK GATES the
#                         loop: the debounce demands 8 *separated* 1 ms samples, so a
#                         correct firmware is still mid-debounce here (it toggles at
#                         ~16.5k). A firmware whose tick stopped gating (e.g. the TMR2IF
#                         poll never re-blocks) free-runs -- but its un-gated loop still
#                         spends a few hundred instruction cycles per sample, so it does
#                         not toggle at the edge; it crosses PRESSED_THRESH at ~14.6k,
#                         ~0.9k cyc (~1.8 ms) BEFORE this checkpoint -> LED already ON
#                         here -> FAIL. (The checkpoint must therefore sit AFTER that
#                         free-run toggle, not right on the edge.)
#   PRESS1_LOW   @ 18.75k : PORTA bit3 == 0 (pressed), LATA bit0 == 1 (LED latched
#                         ENGAGED -- the effect toggled ON the press, not release)
#   ENGAGED      @ 37.5k : LATA bit0 == 1 (LED on, latched), PORTA bit3 == 1
#   BYPASS_AGAIN @ 100k : LATA bit0 == 0 (toggled back off)

stimulus asynchronous_stimulus
  initial_state 1
  { 12500, 0,
    27500, 1,
    65000, 0,
    80000, 1 }
  name fsw
end

node n1
attach n1 fsw ra3

break c 11250
run
echo ===INIT_BYPASS===
porta
lata

break c 15500
run
echo ===PRESS1_EARLY===
porta
lata

break c 18750
run
echo ===PRESS1_LOW===
porta
lata

break c 37500
run
echo ===ENGAGED===
porta
lata

break c 100000
run
echo ===BYPASS_AGAIN===
porta
lata

quit
